# The `mosaic` package (optional)

The `mosaic` package provides a consistent and user-friendly interface for descriptive statistics, plots and inference. You may find it useful to complete an interactive tutorial on its plotting functions. (note: this is optional and will not be counted for any marks). First install the following packages:

```{r, eval=FALSE}
install.packages(c("learnr","mosaic"), 
                 dependencies = TRUE)
```

Then, from RStudio, run the following command which will open a new page in your web broswer:

```{r, eval=FALSE}
learnr::run_tutorial("introduction", 
                     package = "ggformula")
```

A more advanced tutorial on customizing your plots is available also:

```{r, eval=FALSE}
learnr::run_tutorial("refining", 
                     package = "ggformula")
```



# Age-structures of Populations, then and now

The 1911 census of Ireland was taken on April 2nd 1911 and were released to the public in 1961. Follow [this link](http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/help/about19011911census.html) for further details on the census. James Hanley (JH) has scrapped the data and has provided you with a [three column .csv file]() which you can read into `R` using the following command:


1. Sign up for a free DataCamp account at [this link](https://www.datacamp.com/groups/shared_links/4c7d78a632b557dfdd6618b3e8fac09495571fec). Note: you are required to sign up with a `@mail.mcgill.ca` or `@mcgill.ca` email address.  
2. Sign in to [https://github.mcgill.ca/](https://github.mcgill.ca/) using your McGill email address and corresponding password.  

```{r, eval=FALSE}
dat <- read.table("~/git_repositories/epib607/data/age_sex_frequencies_ireland.txt", header = TRUE)
library(dplyr)
dat <- dat %>% mutate(Male = case_when(Male == 1 ~ "Male", Male == 0 ~ "Female"))
colnames(dat) <- c("Gender", "Age", "Freq")
write.csv(dat, file = "data/age_sex_frequencies_ireland.csv", quote = FALSE, row.names = FALSE)


library(rmarkdown)
draft("mypaper.Rmd", template="pdf", package="pinp", edit=TRUE)

```



